<div id="review_1411405972" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1411405972" />
    <a title="Katya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7382340-katya"><img alt="Katya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1326146266p2/7382340.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1411405972?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katya" href="/user/show/7382340-katya">Katya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1411405972" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10456382550685901973">I read this together with A Country Doctor&apos;s Notebook, so this review addresses both works. <br/><br/>It hit really deep, paining me (in a good way) with harsh realities, incisive observations of human nature, and delicious sarcasm. The young doctor&apos;s start to his career put my own into perspective, and, I must say, assured me yet again that medicine would not have been the right choice. The quality of mind and character required to withstand the challenges of that job left me with utmost respect for the </span>
  <span id="freeText10456382550685901973" style="display:none">I read this together with A Country Doctor's Notebook, so this review addresses both works. <br /><br />It hit really deep, paining me (in a good way) with harsh realities, incisive observations of human nature, and delicious sarcasm. The young doctor's start to his career put my own into perspective, and, I must say, assured me yet again that medicine would not have been the right choice. The quality of mind and character required to withstand the challenges of that job left me with utmost respect for the practitioner. <br /><br />It needs hardly be said that Bulgakov writes brilliantly. It is rare, these days, that I find a book I cannot put down. His language is vivid, full of pithy remarks. Balancing his accurate observations, is a very fine sense of the ridiculous. <br /><br />It seems tacky to talk about lessons in literature, but I have to go there. After all, this is a kind of bildungsroman. The essential lesson, earned throughout the stories in different ways, is courage, self-reliance, and humility. Physical ails are one thing, but ignorance, escapism, self-destruction, all these thrive in vulnerable human psychology. In the face of ills he cannot cure, the doctor has to deal with the most unbearable state - helplessness. <br /><br />Humility and strength lies in fighting all the battles the doctor can possibly manage, while not drowning in the things he cannot change. He sees others succumb as often to their own human nature as to illnesses, and has to deal first-hand, every day, with the world's stupid imperfections. Strength is that he doesn't turn his back on it all.<br /><br />A final note on why I enjoy Bulgakov. Morphine, about the devolution of an addict, elicits compassion due to psychological accuracy, rather than sentimentality. The truth is always enough, is always tragicomic and troubled enough, without ornamentation. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10456382550685901973" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


